{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26a90809-c35d-4b11-a984-95906f053aac","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `1` (true), it changes how CLR v4 handles assemblies built against CLR v2:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds legacy mixed-mode (managed + native) assemblies and COM activation requests to the CLR v4 runtime instead of requiring CLR v2.\n- CLR v4 \"takes ownership\" of components that would otherwise demand the v2 runtime.\n\n**Effect on runtime selection:**\n- Without it: loading a CLR v2 mixed-mode assembly triggers a side-by-side v2 activation or fails.\n- With it: CLR v4 loads those assemblies itself, suppressing v2 activation.\n\n**Configured via app.config:**\n```xml\n<startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">\n  <supportedRuntime version=\"v4.0\"/>\n</startup>\n```\n\n**When you'd see this:** hosting legacy COM components, P/Invoke-heavy libraries, or mixed-mode C++/CLI assemblies originally targeting .NET 2.0/3.5 inside a .NET 4+ process.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92eb7513-8024-4505-852e-bcf1bf11fd39","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a specific CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation log message: \"UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy is set to 1\". They want to understand what it means and how it affects runtime selection.\n\nThis is a question about .NET CLR internals - specifically about the legacy runtime activation policy. Let me answer from my knowledge:\n\nThe `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is a configuration setting in .NET that affects how the CLR handles mixed-mode assemblies (assemblies containing both managed and native code) that were built against .NET Framework 2.0/3.5.\n\nWhen set to `1` (true):\n\n\n- It enables CLR v4 to load and run assemblies originally built for CLR v2 without needing a separate v2 instance\n- Legacy COM activations get routed to the current v4 runtime instead of their original compiled version\n- Mixed-mode assemblies targeting CLR v2 will execute within the CLR v4 process\n\nThis is typically configured in an app.config file with a startup element that specifies the legacy policy and supported runtime version. The effect is that older assemblies can coexist and run in newer runtime environments.\n\nWithout this setting, attempting to load a CLR v2 mixed-mode assembly would either trigger a side-by-side CLR v2 activation or fail entirely. Enabling it allows CLR v4 to act as a compatibility layer, handling those legacy assemblies directly.","outputTokens":668,"requestId":"680A:30221B:DCC8F1:EBC42C:6A0B03F3"},"id":"2e53b1f1-dcf1-4171-a2eb-db2fd00e816c","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:20:19.094Z","parentId":"4913221b-d294-4ca6-8efd-3a5d42282326"}
